numcols="2"><single><ipbforeword security="u" sssn="22-00-00"><?Pub Lcl
_divid="400" _parentid="0"><para0><title>General</title>
<para>This partial illustrated parts breakdown is divided into four
chapters:<tabmat frame="none" colsep="0" pgwide="0"><tgroup cols="2">
<colspec colname="col1" colwidth="1.16in"><colspec colname="col2"
colwidth="1.99in"><tbody><row><entry></entry><entry></entry></row><row>
<entry>Chapter 1</entry><entry>Foreword</entry></row><row><entry>Chapter
2</entry><entry>Maintenance Parts List</entry></row><row><entry>Chapter
3</entry><entry>Numerical Index</entry></row><row><entry>Chapter 4</entry>
<entry>Reference Designator Index</entry></row><row><entry></entry>
<entry></entry></row></tbody></tgroup></tabmat></para>
<step1><para>IPB Foreword contains information about this manual</para>
</step1>
<step1><para>The <acronym><def>Maintenance Parts List</def><term>MPL</term>
</acronym> contains all the parts for this system.</para>
</step1>
<step1><para>The <acronym><def>Numerical Index</def><term>NI</term>
</acronym> list each part in this manual and reference to find the
part.</para>
</step1>
<step1><para>The <acronym><def>Reference Designator Index</def><term>RDI</term>
</acronym> list each RDI in this manual and the reference to find
the RDI,</para>
</step1>
</para0>
<para0><title>Organizational</title>
<subpara1><title>Maintenance Parts List</title><para>The maintenance
parts list (MPL) is a series of listings of components of the assemblies
and subassemblies of the aircraft. Each listing is supported by an
illustration. An explanation of the content of each of the MPL columns
is provided in the following paragraphs.</para>
<subpara2><title>Figure and Index Number</title><para>The figure and
index number column provides a key whereby a component within a particular
figure may be related to the accompanying illustration.</para>
<subpara3><title>Part Number</title><para>The part numbers contained
in this book are those established by the design activity.</para>
<subpara4><title>Commercial and Government Entity (CAGE) Codes for
Manufactures or Contractors</title><para>This column identifies the
manufacturer or Government agency having cognizance of the part. All <emphasis
type="i">CAGE</emphasis>codes are taken from Cataloging Handbook H4/H8.
When no CAGE has been assigned, the word <emphasis type="b">"NONE"</emphasis>shall
appear in this column and the manufacturer's complete name and address
shall appear following the description of the part.</para>
<subpara5><title>Description</title><para>This column contains the
description of the part established by the design activity. Part descriptions
are indented to show relationship to their next higher assembly (NHA).
Parts used to attach components are identified with the symbol (AP)
immediately following the part description.<randlist>
<item>First item in a random list</item>
<item>Second item in a random list</item>
<item>Third item in a random list</item>
<item>Fourth item in a random list</item>
</randlist></para>
<subpara6><title>Units Per Assembly</title><para>The quantity shown
in this column represents the quantity required for a single assembly
or subassembly. The abbreviation "AR" (as required) is used when the
quantity must be determined at installation.</para>
<subpara7><title>Numerical Index</title><para>The numerical index
(in alphanumeric order) contains a list of all part numbers appearing
in the MPL cross-reference to the applicable figure and index number.</para>
<subpara8><title>Reference Designator Index</title><para>The reference
designation index is a listing of all parts having reference designations.<seqlist>
<item>First item in a sequential list</item><item>Second item in a
sequential list</item><item>Third item in a sequential list</item><item>Fourth
item in a sequential list</item></seqlist></para>
</subpara8>
</subpara7>
</subpara6>
</subpara5>
</subpara4>
</subpara3>
</subpara2>
</subpara1>
</para0>
<modelcover><title>Models Covered</title><?Pub _bookmark
Command="[Quickmark]"><para>Some Organization use this first paragraph
to explain what this <acronym><def>Illustrated Parts Breakdown</def>
<term>IPB</term></acronym> contains. An example would be, &ldquo;This
Illustrated Parts Breakdown contains a list of all the parts necessary
for the XXXX system.</para>
<subpara1><title>Models Covered Subparagraph</title><para>This is
a models covered first subparagraph. This is a models covered first
subparagraph. This is a models covered first subparagraph. This is
a models covered first subparagraph. This is a models covered first
subparagraph.</para>
</subpara1>
<subpara1><title>This is a Models Covered Second Subparagraph One</title>
<para>This is a models covered first subparagraph. This is a models
covered second subparagraph one. This is a models covered second subparagraph
one. This is a models covered second subparagraph one.</para>
</subpara1>
</modelcover>
<serialization><title>This Paragraph Explains the Usable On Codes</title>
<para>This paragraph explains the usable on Codes. When breakdown
of similar models are combined in the same IPB, part variations within
the models are indicated by a letter symbol in the USABLE ON CODE
column. Where the USABLE ON CODE column has been left blank part listed
applies to all models covered by this breakdown.</para>
<sertable frame="none" colsep="1" rowsep="1" pgwide="0">
<serrow><nomen>AN/ARN-186(1) VHF Radio</nomen><modelno>XXX-XX</modelno>
<serno>12345</serno></serrow>
<serrow><nomen>AN/ARN-186(1) VHF Radio</nomen><modelno>ZZZ-ZZ</modelno>
<serno>12346</serno></serrow>
</sertable>
</serialization>
<finding><title>Optional How to Find Part Numbers, Illustration, and
Description</title><para>This is the place where the usual two &ldquo;How
to find&rdquo; graphics are inserted. Some Organizations use a Para0
at the end of the IPB Foreword to insert the &ldquo;How to&rdquo;
graphics.</para>
</finding>
<simassem><title>Optional Listing of Similar Assemblies</title><para>There
are no similar assemblies in this Illustrated Parts Breakdown.</para>
</simassem>
<quickchgexpl><title>Optional Quick Change Information</title><para>A
table can be added to list the parts in a kit or quick change unit.</para>
</quickchgexpl>
<symsect rtermwidth="2.5in" ltermwidth="1.10in"><title>Symbol Definition</title>
<para>The following list of symbols are used in this manual and adhere
to requirements of DoD specification MIL-STD-38784.</para>
<symtitle>List of Symbols</symtitle>
<term security="u"><graphic boardno="ESD1"></term><def>This is the
symbol used to indicate Electrostatic Discharge Sensitive parts. ESDS
parts require to be handled in accordance with the ESDS device handling
procedures in TO 00-25-234.  This explanation shall be preceded by
a CAUTION heading.</def>
<term>**HCI**</term><def>This is the symbol used for a Harness Critical
Item. This shall include an explanation that the HCI symbol establishes
special requirements limiting changes and substitutions, and that
the specific parts listed must be used to ensure hardness is not degraded.
 This statement shall be preceded by a CAUTION heading.</def>
</symsect>
<abbrsect><title>List of Standard Abbreviations and Acronyms</title>
<para>This publication provides a list of standard abbreviations and
acronyms used throughout this document.</para>
<abbrtitle>List of Abbreviations and Acronyms</abbrtitle>
<acronymlist autobuild="1">
</abbrsect>
<shtnoexpl><title>Optional Explanation of the Sheet Number</title><para>This
paragraph is used to explain the use of sheet numbers in an Illustrated
Parts Breakdown. If multiple sheet illustrations are used, an explanation
shall be included that the sheet number follows the index number and
is separated with a slash (/). The explanation shall also state that,
if an indexed item is on more than one sheet of an illustration, the
first and last sheet numbers on which the item appears are given.</para>
</shtnoexpl>
<useonexpl><title>This Paragraph Explains the Usable on Codes</title>
<para>This paragraph explains the usable on Codes. When breakdown
of similar models are combined in the same IPB, part variations within
the models are indicated by a letter symbol in the USABLE ON CODE
column. Where the USABLE ON CODE column has been left blank part listed
applies to all models covered by this breakdown.</para>
</useonexpl>
<smrexpl><title>Source Maintenance and Recoverability Code Explanation</title>
<para>This paragraph explains the <acronym><def>Source Maintenance
and Recoverability Code</def><term>SMR</term></acronym>. This Manual
contains Joint Military Services Uniform SMR codes. Source and Repair
Codes assigned by the Government and furnished by the procuring activity.
Definitions of these codes are available in TO 00-25-195.</para>
</smrexpl>
<ipbhci><title><hci> Nuclear Hardness</title><para>If equipment covered
has nuclear survivability requirements (for example, Over Pressure
and Burst, Thermal Radiation, Electromagnetic Pulse, or Transient
Radiation Effects on Electronics), all Hardness Critical Items (HCI)
shall be marked. Unless otherwise specified by the acquiring activity,
all HCIs shall be marked with the symbol  HCI immediately preceding
the description of the item. When approved by the acquiring activity,
the symbol **HCI** may be used in lieu of the boxed HCI symbol. </para>
<subpara1><title>Nuclear Hardness Symbol Explanation</title>
<caution>
<para>All changes to, or proposed substitutions of, HCIs must be approved
by the acquiring activity.</para>
</caution>
<para>Chapter 1 shall include a listing and explanation of the HCI
symbol and other pertinent information, as necessary, to emphasize
the uniqueness of hardness features.  This shall include an explanation
that the HCI symbol establishes special requirements limiting changes
and substitutions, and that the specific parts listed must be used
to ensure hardness is not degraded. This statement shall be preceded
by a CAUTION heading. All changes to, or proposed substitutions of,
HCIs must be approved by the acquiring activity.</para>
</subpara1>
</ipbhci>
<ipbesds><title><esds> Electrostatic Discharge Sensitive (ESDS) Parts</title>
<caution>
<para>The present of an ESDS symbol requires that all ESDS parts be
handled in accordance with the ESDS device handling procedures in
TO 00-25</para>
</caution>
<para>If equipment covered contains ESDS parts, they shall be marked.
 Unless otherwise specified by the acquiring activity, all ESDS parts
shall be marked with the ESDS symbol <esds> immediately preceding
the description of the item .When approved by the acquiring activity,
the symbol **ESD** may be used in lieu of the ESDS symbol. </para>
</ipbesds>
<partstd><title>Part Standardization</title><para>This paragraph explains
Part Standardization. Authority for use of a part number different
than the part number  listed in this IPB is established by the Department
of Defense (DoD) Interchangeability and Substitution Program. Refer
to the DO43B Master Item Identification Base for Air Force information.
The maintenance technician has final responsibility and authority
for determining acceptability of substitute parts.</para>
</partstd>
<mfrlist><title>Manufacturers List</title><para>When required by the
acquiring activity, a manufacturers list shall be provided. The list
shall contain the <acronym><def>Commercial and Government Entity </def>
<term>CAGE</term></acronym> code and the name and address of all manufacturers
whose CAGE codes are referenced in the MPL.</para>
</mfrlist>
